import static org.junit.jupiter.api.Assertions.assertEquals;
import static org.junit.jupiter.api.Assertions.assertFalse;
import static org.junit.jupiter.api.Assertions.assertThrows;

import java.io.File;
import java.io.IOException;
import java.nio.charset.StandardCharsets;
import java.nio.file.Files;
import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.Arrays;
import java.util.List;

import org.junit.jupiter.api.DisplayName;
import org.junit.jupiter.api.Test;
import org.davidmoten.text.utils.WordWrap; // Ensure this import is present
public class WordWrap_wrap_2_Test {

    @Test
    @DisplayName("wrap(String filename, Charset) writes wrapped output to named file and reads it back via wrapUtf8(String)")
    public void test_TC17() throws IOException {
        // GIVEN: text that upon wrapping will produce predictable output
        String text = "alpha beta gamma";
        String tmpFilename = Files.createTempFile("ww", ".txt").toString();
        // WHEN: write wrapped output to file via overload
        WordWrap.from(text).maxWidth(6).wrap(tmpFilename, StandardCharsets.UTF_8);
        // read back the file and also get direct wrap
        String fileContent = new String(Files.readAllBytes(new File(tmpFilename).toPath()), StandardCharsets.UTF_8);
        String direct = WordWrap.from(text).maxWidth(6).wrap();
        // THEN: file content equals direct wrap output
        assertEquals(direct, fileContent);
        // cleanup
        new File(tmpFilename).delete();
    }

    @Test
    @DisplayName("from(File,Charset) throws IORuntimeException when input file not found")
    public void test_TC18() {
        // GIVEN: non-existent file reference
        File f = new File("nonexistent_file_hopefully_does_not_exist.txt");
        // WHEN/THEN: from(File,Charset) should throw IORuntimeException
        assertThrows(IORuntimeException.class, () -> WordWrap.from(f, StandardCharsets.UTF_8));
    }

    @Test
    @DisplayName("Long word broken without hyphens when insertHyphens=false and breakWords=true (writeBrokenWord else-branch)")
    public void test_TC19() {
        // GIVEN: single long word to force breakWords path without hyphens
        String w = "abcdef"; // length 6 > maxWidth
        // WHEN: set maxWidth small, enable breakWords and disable hyphens
        String result = WordWrap.from(w)
                .maxWidth(2)                // force tooLong on first word fragment
                .breakWords(true)           // allow breaking words
                .insertHyphens(false)       // disable hyphens so else branch in writeBrokenWord
                .wrap();
        // THEN: result starts with at least two chars and contains a newline, and no hyphens
        assertEquals(true, result.startsWith("ab"), "Expected result to start with broken fragment 'ab'");
        assertEquals(true, result.contains("\n"), "Expected a line break in broken word output");
        assertFalse(result.contains("-"), "Expected no hyphens when insertHyphens is false");
    }

    @Test
    @DisplayName("Trailing spaces before newline are trimmed by rightTrim path")
    public void test_TC20() {
        // GIVEN: text with trailing spaces before explicit newline
        String text = "foo    \n";
        // WHEN: wrap with default settings should trim trailing spaces on newline
        String result = WordWrap.from(text).wrap();
        // THEN: trailing spaces removed, only 'foo' and newline remain
        assertEquals("foo\n", result);
    }

    @Test
    @DisplayName("wrap(LineConsumer) uses custom consumer to collect char arrays and newLine events")
    public void test_TC21() {
        // GIVEN: custom LineConsumer collecting writes and new lines
        List<String> parts = new ArrayList<>();
        LineConsumer consumer = new LineConsumer() {
            @Override
            public void write(char[] chars, int off, int len) {
                parts.add(new String(chars, off, len));
            }

            @Override
            public void writeNewLine() {
                parts.add("<NL>");
            }

            @Override
            public void write(String s) throws IOException {
                // Not used in this test
                parts.add(s);
            }
        };
        // WHEN: wrap text "a bc" with maxWidth 1 causes each char on its own line via consumer
        WordWrap.from("a bc").maxWidth(1).wrap(consumer);
        // THEN: parts list should reflect individual chars and new line tokens
        List<String> expected = Arrays.asList("a", "<NL>", "b", "<NL>", "c");
        assertEquals(expected, parts);
    }
}
- Error Log Message: 

2) **What to Produce**
- Output a single JSON object containing an array named `"ErrorGuides"`.
- Each element of `"ErrorGuides"` MUST have exactly these keys:
  - `"ErrorSpot"`: A precise pointer to the error location (e.g., method name, file path + line number, or `"import section"`). If it is an import error, specify `"import section"` and the file.
  - `"ErrorCause"`: A concise English description of the root cause (why it failed).
  - `"ErrorGuide"`: A pseudocode-style, step-by-step fix guide in English.
  - `"Before"`: The minimal code fragment (or signature) that is wrong.
  - `"After"`: The corrected minimal code fragment (or signature) that should replace the `"Before"`.
- Only report issues that are evidenced by the provided error log. Do not invent additional problems.
- If multiple errors exist, list them in the order they appear in the log.

3) **Constraints**
- Do NOT change the number of test scenarios (this prompt does not ask you to output fixed tests).
- Keep fixes minimal and focused strictly on the error causes shown in the log.
- If the error references a missing/invalid constructor or generic type inference failure, show the corrected constructor/generics explicitly in `"After"`.
- If the error references class/file name mismatch, `"ErrorSpot"` must include both the public class name and the filename, and `"Before"`/`"After"` must reflect the correct pairing.
- If reflection access or import is the issue, set fields accessible and ensure imports are correct, but only if such errors are indicated in the log.
- Avoid mocks/abstractions unless the log directly points to them.

4) **Style**
- All explanations (`"ErrorCause"` and `"ErrorGuide"`) should be in **English**.
- Keep `"Before"`/`"After"` as short, minimal code blocks or single-line signatures where possible.
- If line numbers are present in the log, include them in `"ErrorSpot"` (e.g., `"…Test.java:123:45"`).

[Error Categories to Handle]
You must analyze and report all errors from the following categories:
  1) Type: Syntax / Compile Error
  Description: Missing import, invalid class, wrong method signature, incompatible types
  Examples: “cannot find symbol”, “missing return statement”, “incompatible types”

  2) Type: Runtime Error
  Description: Exception occurring during test execution
  Examples: “NullPointerException”, “IndexOutOfBoundsException”, “IllegalArgumentException”


[Rules for Each Error Type]
  1) Compile-Time Errors:
  Identify incorrect syntax, type, import, or constructor.
  Include file and class name if mismatched.
  Keep “Before” and “After” minimal and focused.

  2) Runtime Errors:
  Specify which statement threw the exception.
  Suggest fixes such as null checks, bounds checks, or proper initialization.


[Emphasis/Request]
- Minimize changes; focus on compilability/run-ability per the error log.
- Never summarize or remove scenarios; this prompt is ONLY for producing Error Guides.
- Ensure steps are practical and do not introduce infinite loops or unrelated edits.

[Output Format]
Return ONLY one JSON object, enclosed in triple backticks as `"json"`. The schema MUST be:

```json
{
  "ErrorGuides": [
    {
      "ErrorSpot": "<file path or class#method or 'import section'>",
      "ErrorCause": "<short and clear explanation of the cause>",
      "ErrorGuide": "<pseudocode-style step-by-step fix guide>",
      "Before": "<minimal code snippet that is wrong>",
      "After": "<corrected minimal code snippet>"
    }
    // ... more errors in log order
  ]
}

[SUMMARY]
Output strictly JSON (no extra text or markdown).
Focus only on real, logged issues.
Ensure minimal, safe, and realistic fixes.
Avoid any fix that could introduce infinite loops or unbounded execution.
Goal: Produce a clean, precise, developer-ready Error Guide JSON.
